Task Summary: Interactive Counter Widget
1. Library Integration
Imported PySide6, the Python framework for Qt, to build a cross-platform graphical user interface (GUI).

Utilized specific widgets like QLineEdit for display and QPushButton for user interaction.

2. Dynamic Logic Initialization
Created a custom class Tlacitko inheriting from QWidget.

Implemented a conditional starting value: the counter defaults to 20 for a 2-player game and 40 for other formats, showing you've planned for different game modes.

3. UI Component Construction
Display: Added a QLineEdit to show the current number, centered the text, and set it to expand to fill available space.

Controls: Created three buttons:

+ (Plus) for incrementing.

- (Minus) for decrementing.

Barva (Color) intended for UI customization or player identification.

4. Advanced Layout Management
Nested Layouts: Used a QVBoxLayout (vertical) for the buttons and nested it inside a QHBoxLayout (horizontal) to sit alongside the display.

Proportional Scaling: Used stretch factors (7 for the input, 3 for the buttons) to ensure the display takes up 70% of the width while the buttons take up 30%.

Size Policies: Set Expanding policies so the elements grow or shrink smoothly if the window is resized.

5. Application Lifecycle
Established the standard if __name__ == "__main__": entry point to initialize the QApplication, set an initial window size (400x200), and start the event loop.
